eems like a straightforward solution!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating package options**\\n\\nI'm considering the need for a helper package defined in the child directory. It looks like loading nested definitions might be necessary, so I'm thinking of using the parent package marker from `io_projectreactor_tools.blockhound.parentpackage`. I'll need to create a marker Java file, but I'm wondering if that’s an extra step. Maybe I can just use the existing parent package from JUnit or `org.assertj.core.api`, but there could be potential issues with class collisions in generated classes. It's a bit complicated!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring package loading**\\n\\nI’m considering how to create a `RejectingPackageClassLoader` that overrides `protected Package getPackage(String name)`. Even though it’s deprecated, it’s still a possibility. I think it could return something like `UsingUnsafeOverrideExercise.class.getPackage()` for the target subpackage. But I'm concerned about potential package name mismatches. The package object might have a different name, and it seems like `definition.isCompatibleTo` only checks the seal. I'll need to clarify that.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_38qfs4FJXB0Y142yf4aX8E66|fc_0048ece5fd6cb84b016a291dfd57008197a90e3e070e61722f", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "python3 - <<'PY'\nimport urllib.request\nurl='https://raw.githubusercontent.com/raphw/byte-buddy/byte-buddy-1.14.4/byte-buddy-dep/src/main/java/net/bytebuddy/dynamic/loading/PackageDefinitionStrategy.java'\ntext=urllib.request.urlopen(url, timeout=10).read().decode().splitlines()\nfor i,l in enumerate(text):\n if 'boolean isCompatibleTo' in l or 'class Simple' in l:\n  print(i+1,l)\nfor i in range(90, 170): print(f'{i+1}: {text[i]}')\nPY", "timeout": 15}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1407, "output": 2694, "cacheRead": 36352, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 40453